Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop onto a large #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{for roasting}, sprinkle with the @dried rosemary{1%tsp} and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway
through.

Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}. Chop the @tomato{1%medium} into small 1cm pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

When the potatoes have ~{10%minutes} of cooking time left, heat a drizzle of @oil{for frying}
in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Season the @sea bass fillets{2} with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

Once hot, carefully place your sea bass into the pan, skin-side down. Cook for ~{3-4%minutes}
before turning over and cooking for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> To get crispy skin on the fish, don't move it around when it's cooking skin-side down.

When cooked, transfer to a #plate{} to rest and cover with #foil{} to keep warm.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish. The fish is cooked
> when opaque in the middle.

Wipe out your (now empty) frying pan and pop on medium heat with the @olive oil{for the salsa}.

Once the oil is hot, add the tomato and cook until just warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Gently stir in the garlic and lemon zest and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}. Squeeze
in some lemon juice and season with salt and pepper.

Taste and add more salt, pepper and lemon if needed, then remove from the heat.

Pop the @pea shoots{40} into a #bowl{} with the @pesto dressing{30%g} and toss to coat.

When everything is ready, transfer the sea bass to your plates and spoon over the warm
tomato salsa.

Serve with the rosemary potatoes and pesto salad alongside. Scatter the @walnuts{20} over the
salad to finish. Enjoy!